  "prompt": "What is the difference between enum, union and struct in C programming?",
  "response": "In C programming, `enum`, `union`, and `struct` are different types of user-defined data types that serve various purposes. Here's a detailed comparison of these three:\n\n### Enum (Enumeration)\nAn `enum` is a custom data type that allows you to define a set of named integer constants. Enumerations are primarily used to assign names to constant values, making the code more readable and maintainable. \n\n#### Example:\n```c\nenum Day {\n    SUNDAY,    // 0\n    MONDAY,    // 1\n    TUESDAY,   // 2\n    WEDNESDAY, // 3\n    THURSDAY,  // 4\n    FRIDAY,    // 5\n    SATURDAY   // 6\n};\n```\n#### Key Points:\n- By default, the values start at 0 and increment by 1 for each subsequent name.\n- You can explicitly assign values to the names if required.\n- Enumerations help in defining a variable type that can take one of a set of predefined values.\n\n### Union\nA `union` is a custom data type where all members share the same memory location. This means that at any given time, you can only store a value in one of the members. The size of a union is determined by the size of its largest member.\n\n#### Example:\n```c\nunion Data {\n    int i;\n    float f;\n    char str[20];\n};\n```\n#### Key Points:\n- All members of a union occupy the same memory space.\n- Only one member can contain a value at any one time.\n- Useful when you need to store a variable that can take multiple types, but only one at a time, saving memory.\n\n### Struct (Structure)\nA `struct` is a custom data type that groups related variables (members) into a single unit. Each member within a structure has its own memory space, allowing you to store different types of data together.\n\n#### Example:\n```c\nstruct Person {\n    char name[50];\n    int age;\n    float height;\n};\n```\n#### Key Points:\n- Each member of a structure has unique memory space.\n- Members can be of different data types.\n- Structures are useful for grouping different types of data together, like a record in a database.\n\n### Comparison Summary:\n- **Enum**: Used for defining a set of integer constants representing discrete values.\n- **Union**: Members share the same memory location, designed for memory-efficient storage of variables that can take different types, one at a time.\n- **Struct**: Members have separate memory locations, used for grouping different types of data together into a single unit.\n\nChoosing between `enum`, `union`, and `struct` depends on the specific needs of your program. Use `enum` for named constants, `union` for memory-efficient storage of mutually exclusive data, and `struct` for grouping different types of data together.",
